    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p><ol class="HELM_parts"> 

<p>A cross-channel ferry usually takes {@a@} hours to make the {@b@} km crossing from England and France.</p>
<p><li> What is the boat’s average speed? [[input:ans1]] km/h [[feedback:prt1]] [[validation:ans1]] </li></p>
<p><li> Derive a linear model connecting distance from England and time since leaving port. Consider any limitations of the model. [[input:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]] [[validation:ans2]] </li></p>
<p><li> According to this model, when will the boat be {@c@} km and {@d@} km from England in minutes? {@c@}km:[[input:ans3]] [[feedback:prt3]] [[validation:ans3]]</p>
<p>{@d@}km [[input:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]] [[validation:ans4]]</li></p>
<p></p>
<p><li> During one winter, the roads in the country district were completely free from snow when it started snowing at {@e@} a.m. and it snowed steadily all day. At {@f@} a.m. it was {@g@} cm deep. To save money, the local practice was to wait until the snow was {@h@} cm deep before ploughing the roads. Forecast when ploughing would start, stating any assumptions. [[input:ans5]] [[feedback:prt5]] [[input:ans6]] [[feedback:prt6]]  [[validation:ans5]][[validation:ans6]]</li></p>
<li> In a drought, the population of a particular species of water beetle in a pond is observed to have halved when the volume of water in the pond has fallen by half. Make a simple assumption about the relationship between the beetle population and the volume of water in the pond and express this in symbols as an equation. What would your model predict for the population when the water volume is only one third of what it was originally. [[input:ans7]] [[feedback:prt7]]  [[validation:ans7]]</li></p>

<p><li> A firm produces a specialised instrument and, although it has the facilities to produce 100 instruments per week, it rarely produces more than 50. It is finding it difficult to assess the cost of producing the instruments and to set realistic prices. The firm’s accountant estimates that the firm pays out £{@k@} per week on fixed costs (overheads, salaries etc.) and that the additional cost of producing each instrument is £{@l@}. </p>
<p>Derive and use a linear model for the variation in total costs with the quantity of instruments produced, (Number of instruments = i) Cost = [[input:ans8]] [[feedback:prt8]]  [[validation:ans8]]. State any limitation of this model [[input:ans9]] [[feedback:prt9]][[validation:ans9]]. </p>
<p>What is the model’s prediction for the cost of producing {@m@} instruments per week? [[input:ans10]] [[feedback:prt10]]  [[validation:ans10]]. </li>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p><li> Speed = distance/ time, as the units are the same no conversion is needed</li></p>
<p><li>As the initial distance at t=0 is equal to 0, that means the equation is d = speed * time</li></p>
<p><li> Time = distance / speed, however the question asks in minutes therefore conversions from hours to minutes is needed.</li></p>
<p><li>Firstly work out the amount of snow falling per hour({@g@}/({@f@}-{@e@})), then work out the height of snow needed to reach the ploughing limit ({@h@} - {@g@}), then divide the second value by the first and that is the additional time after {@f@}.</li></p>
<p><li>As the question states make a simple assumption, it is wise to assume a direct relationship, therefore if the volume is a third so will the population. </li></p>
<p><li>As the fixed cost is {@k@}, this does not vary, therefore this will be independant of the number of instruments, as {@i@} is the cost to make the instrument this varies with i, therefore the formula is cost = {@k@} + {@l@}* i</p>
<p> As the firm state their maximum production rate is 100 this is a limitation of the model therefore we will say the model applies for a range (0≤i≤100)</p>
<p>To predict the cost of {@m@} instruments, use the formula above cost = {@k@} + {@l@} * {@m@}</li></p>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
